ssical Roman Philosophy on Legal Subjectivity -- tPart III: History (Non-Western and Western) -- tPursuits of Global Gendered Intellectual History: Stories from India -- tYosano Akikoʼs Philosophy and Poetry – Modernization of Japan and Womenʼs Liberation -- tA Philosophical Defense of Self-Defense: Examining Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz’ Reply to Sor Filotea -- tLe rôle des oeuvres de Rousseau dans les mouvements féministes en Chine moderne -- tMind of Nature: Cavendish’s Argument for Panpsychism -- tFirst Principles: The Path to Women’s Emancipation in Wollstonecraft’s Rights of Woman -- tWomen’s Access to French Philosophy: A Forgotten History (1880–1924) -- tHannah Höch: Notes on Violence and Vulnerability -- tPart IV: Gender Issues and Feminist Concepts -- tFeminist Philosophy and Democracy: The Case of Spain -- tGender Equality in Colombia’s Philosophy Programs: Faculty Participation -- tTeaching Islamic Feminisms in the History of Philosophy in Mexico: A Decolonial and Feminist Effort -- tFrom Self-awareness to Political and Social Improvement: A Feminist Identitarian Path -- t“Je me révolte, donc nous sommes”: Reconceptualizing Contemporary Refugee Resistances through the Butlerian Reconstruction of Hannah Arendt’s Public Sphere -- tCovid-19 and “Stay at Home”: A Contrast Dye That Highlights Gender Violence and the Violence of Inequity -- tA New-old Topos for the Future. Rethinking and Rediscovering Oneself as Human -- tContributors to This Volume -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn times of current crisis, the voices of women are needed more than ever. The accumulation of war and environmental catastrophes teaches us that exploitation of people and nature through violent appropriation and enrichment for the sake of short-term self-interest exacts its price. This book presents contributions on the currently most relevant and most urgent issues: reshaping the economy, environmental problems, technology and the re-reading of history from the non-western and western tradition. With an outlook into the problems of class, race and gender in its intersectional framing, the collection offers a unique overview of current research in these fields and contributes to the renewal and contemporary presentation of feminist thought from partly concrete perspectives with regard to factual issues.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeschlecht. 4aGleichstellung. 4aRasse. 4afeministische Philosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aequality.  afeminist philosophy.  agender.  arace.1 aAcevedo-Zapata, Diana María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlloni, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAttri, Shalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaizabal, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonfim, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnet, Annabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasi, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeGriselles, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeibel, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalcão Pricladnitzky, Pedro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaudiano, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiardini, Federica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGünter, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagen